{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636330"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:26:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:26:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17579"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17579"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10269"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71370"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10269"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17579"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56845"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10072"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24002"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71370"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELow density lipoprotein (LDL) particles play a crucial role in cholesterol transport and metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how LDL particles are taken up by liver cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Phagocytosis by hepatic Kupffer cells","Active transport through membrane channels","Facilitated diffusion via specific carrier proteins","Passive diffusion across the cell membrane","Receptor-mediated endocytosis via binding to apolipoprotein B-100"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELDL particles are primarily taken up by hepatocytes through \u003Cstrong\u003Ereceptor-mediated endocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E. This process involves the binding of apolipoprotein B-100 on the LDL particle surface to specific LDL receptors on the hepatocyte membrane. The receptor-LDL complex is then internalised in clathrin-coated vesicles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion across the cell membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - LDL particles are too large to diffuse across cell membranes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport through membrane channels\u003C/strong\u003E - No specific channels exist for LDL particle transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitated diffusion via specific carrier proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - LDL particles require energy-dependent endocytosis rather than facilitated diffusion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhagocytosis by hepatic Kupffer cells\u003C/strong\u003E - While Kupffer cells can phagocytose modified LDL, this is not the primary uptake mechanism for normal LDL particles\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter internalisation, the LDL particle is broken down in lysosomes, releasing cholesterol for cellular use. The number of LDL receptors is regulated through negative feedback based on intracellular cholesterol levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Low density lipoprotein (LDL) receptors on hepatocytes bind to apolipoprotein B-100 on LDL particles to facilitate cholesterol uptake.","LDL receptor-mediated endocytosis is the primary mechanism for removing cholesterol from circulation.","Intracellular cholesterol levels regulate LDL receptor expression through negative feedback."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56845"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17579"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56845"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T08:58:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T09:04:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10269"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71370"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"